<DOC><DOCNO> AP880901-0138 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-01-88 1351EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-US-Afghanistan     09-01 0148</FIRST><SECOND>AM-US-Afghanistan,150</SECOND><HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan</HEAD><HEAD>State Department Condemns Bomb Attack In Pakistan</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The State Department condemned on Thursday thebombing attack by Afghan-based warplanes in Pakistan, calling itthe ``latest and most extreme incident of armed intervention''against Pakistan's terrorial integrity.   Deputy spokesman Phyllis Oakley said the attack, which occurred40 miles inside Pakistani territory Thursday, was a violation ofthe four-month-old Geneva agreement on Afghanistan.   ``The United States condemns this act of aggression againstPakistan,'' she said. One person was killed and at least 18 werewounded, she said.   She added that the United States will raise the issue with theUnited Nations and with Soviet authorities. For their part,Afghanistan and the Soviet Union have accused Pakistan of violatingthe Geneva agreement by supporting anti-communist Afghan rebels.   Mrs. Oakley said it was not clear whether the planes werepiloted by Soviets or Afghans.</TEXT></DOC>